==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Leitmotiv
<hw>Leit"mo*tiv"</hw></mhw>
<pr>(l⟦imac⟧t"m⟦osl⟧*t⟦esl⟧f")</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[G., leading
motive.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>a guiding theme; in
Wagnerian opera, a marked melodic phrase or short musical passage which
always accompanies the reappearance of a certain person, situation,
abstract idea, or allusion in the course of the play; a sort of musical
label. Also called <cref>Leading motive</cref>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source> <source>+PJC</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>a recurring theme in the activities of a person or
group.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>PJC</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Leitneria</ent>⟦br⟧
